{
  "text": "For many years the equine roundworm has been named Parascaris equorum in veterinary investigations. However, a recent study from U.S [CITATION_1] observed that the dominant species infecting equines is most likely Parascaris univalens and not P. equorum. These species are identical apart from the fact that P. univalens has two chromosomes, and not four as in P. equorum [CITATION_2] . However, concurrently we have shown with genetic tools that the global Parascaris spp population, including worms from the U.S later identified as P. univalens, is essentially homogeneous [CITATION_3] . Thus, equine roundworms previously described as P. equorum in Sweden and in several other countries have most likely been misidentified and are probably identical to P. univalens.",
  "correct_citation": {
